summary:
Limitations on Student Athlete NIL Conduct
The Michigan NIL Law does not allow athletes to endorse:
alcohol;
tobacco;
gambling;
weapons;
pharmaceuticals;
banned athletic substances;
drugs or drug paraphernalia; or
adult entertainment.
Athletes must disclose proposed NIL contracts, including projected compensation, to a designated official at the school, and must not conflict with school contracts, policies, or rules.
Athletes cannot engage in NIL activities during games or practices.
NIL Agents/Advisors/Representatives
Agents and attorneys hired by athletes must be licensed by the state.

New Jersey NIL started on July 1, 2021, per the NCAA Interim Policies and with the passage of State Bill 971 and will take effect in the fifth academic year following the date of enactment.
Permissible NIL Conduct
The NIL laws in New Jersey allow athletes to hire an agent to represent their NIL interests and it prevents an athlete from being declared ineligible from monetizing their NIL.
Limitations on NIL Activities (for Educational Institutions)
The law forbids:
deals that conflict with a team contract;
deals with adult entertainment products and services;
alcohol;
gambling;
tobacco;
pharmaceuticals;
controlled “dangerous” substances; and
weapons.
Violations could result in an athlete losing their scholarship.

Permissible NIL Conduct
Students participating in intercollegiate athletics or who have completed at least their sophomore year of high school and may be eligible to compete in intercollegiate athletics in the future may earn compensation from the use of their name, image, or likeness.
Student athletes may obtain professional or legal representation connected to their NIL activities. Individuals providing professional representation must be registered with the State. Individuals providing legal assistance must be licensed by the State. Athlete agents must comply with the federal Sports Agent Responsibility and Trust Act.
NCAA Division I college athletics programs must offer student athletes assistance programs. These programs may include: a financial distress fund; mental health support services; financial literacy training; degree completion assistance; trainings regarding sex-based discrimination and harassment; leadership training; and career development programs.
Limitations on NIL Activities
Student athletes must disclose potential NIL contracts to college officials prior to execution.
Athletics associations (including the NCAA) cannot prevent a college from identifying, facilitating, enabling, or supporting opportunities for student athletes to earn NIL compensation.
Athletics associations (including the NCAA) cannot authorize its member institutions to:
Prevent a college from participating in intercollegiate athletics because a student athlete has earned or intends to earn NIL compensation;
Entertain a complaint, open an investigation, or take any other adverse action against a college engaging in activity protected under New York’s NIL law or for involvement in student NIL activities; and
Penalize a college because an individual or organization that supports or benefits the college or its athletics programs violates the athletics association’s NIL rules.
Student athletes cannot enter into NIL contracts where those contracts would:
Conflict with provisions of a student athlete’s team contract;
Cause the student to violate the college’s student handbook or code of conduct;
Conflict with a contract or sponsorship of the college;
Cause financial loss or reputational damage to the college;
Require actions by the student athlete during team activities or scheduled classes;
Use the college’s intellectual property;
Require the student athlete to display a sponsor’s product, logo, or brand during team activities;
Require the student athlete to display the product, logo, or brand of a sponsor that competes with a sponsor of the college.

Under North Carolina's executive order, student athletes can earn compensation for their name, image, and likeness. Any policies imposed by previous executive order (No. 223) were rescinded by the current executive order (No. 306). These rescinded policies include:
a restriction on student athletes' ability to earn compensation for their name, image, and likeness as a direct inducement to participate in sports at a particular institution or enroll/continue to be enrolled in an institution for participating in sports;
a restriction on North Carolina colleges and universities' ability to compensate student athletes for use of their name, image, and likeness;
the ability of North Carolina colleges and universities to impose reasonable limitations on a student athlete's ability to receive compensation for their name, image, and likeness; and
a requirement that student athletes comply with certain laws, including the North Carolina Athlete Agent Act, in contracting with NIL representatives.

General Provisions
The March 27, 2025 amendment allows institutions to directly compensate student athletes for their name, image, and likeness, unless the institution uses: (i) funds appropriated by the Legislature, or (ii) a fee paid by a student attending the institution pays to the institution.
Student athlete agreements, and any communications/materials related thereto, are not subject to Utah’s Government Records Access Management Act.
Limitations on NIL Conduct
Student athletes cannot enter into a student athlete agreement promoting:
Tobacco products or e-cigarettes;
Alcohol products;
Seller/dispensers of controlled substances;
Gambling/betting;
A sexually-oriented business;
A firearm that the student cannot legally purchase

Institutional Responsibilities and Limitations
The Utah Board of Higher Education must conduct an audit of state institutions evaluating the money they spend to directly compensate student athletes for their name, image, and likeness and the use of such payments beginning in fiscal year 2028 and every five years thereafter.
Athletic Association Responsibilities and Limitations
Athletic associations or entities may not prevent a student athlete from participating in intercollegiate athletics because they (i) receive compensation for their name, image, and likeness or (ii) obtains professional representation from an athlete agent or attorney.
Athletic associations or entities may also not prevent an institution or other entity from facilitating name, image, and likeness compensation opportunities for student athletes
